<br>
One way is to model the best - but that is just one way of doing things based on what Richard Bandler (who you mentioned in your post) did in the early 1970's.<br>
<br>
There are other ways.<br>
<br>
As well as NLP I learned something called Developmental Behavioural Modelling which focuses more on modelling skills.<br>
I also learned Design Human Engineering which focuses more on engineering new skills and behaviours.<br>
<br>
Think of them kinda like 'fan art' and 'original art' <br>
<br>
Modelling is about developing ways to do what others have already done. DHE is about developing ways to do what no-one else as done.<br>
<br>
For those new to something  'behavioural modelling' is useful to aquire the skills that are to general to what you are doing For those who want to innovate, create new art and new ways to do art then 'behavioural engineering' is useful.<br>
<br>
<br>
Modelling is good for getting the basics and is pretty well covered by books and tutorials (but going back to what I said earlier - it can always be improved upon - ie your idea to model the best artists and find out what they are doing)<br>
<br>
Behavioural Engineering is about stimulating people to begin to consider what doesn't exist and find new ways to achieve this.<br>
<br>
Conceptual Design, original artwork, etc. <br>
<br>
At University I also studied Civil Engineering so I guess I lean more towards the engineering side. <br>
<br>
Getting into more creativity is a wild, wild ride ..... but also lots and lots of FUN.<br>
<br>
Model the best - then go beyond them - thats what I say<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
